<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by The Scottish Federation of Housing Associations</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Scottish Federation of Housing Associations</span></p><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Who We Are</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Scottish Federation of Housing Associations (SFHA) is the national representative body </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Scotland’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> housing associations and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operatives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></h2><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Scope of Evidence</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e welcome the Work and Pensions Committee’s call for evidence on the subject of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing costs support in the revised welfare system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We understand that the Committee wishes to look at: </span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the effects of the changes that have already been introduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the potential impacts of the forthcoming changes; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ways in which housing cost support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> might be provided in the future, as Universal Credit is rolled out nationally.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this submission we specifically address our concerns about:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of the Government’s withdrawal of the ‘spare room subsidy’;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The consequen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> housing associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ finances and operations;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Specific concerns about landlords’ security of income arising from the move to Universal Credit, the introduction of ‘direct payments’ of support for housing costs to the tenant, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact of the Claimant Commitment and sanc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tions regime; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urrent proposals for supporting vulnerable claimants under the terms of the proposed Local Support Service Framework. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e are six months into the implementati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on of the under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">restriction. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e have included in this submission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the evidence that is available to us showing the early impacts of this change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We have also highlighted evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Scottish direct payment demonstration project. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing Benefit is a very significant revenue stream for housing associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The amount and certainty of this revenue stream is under severe threat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recent and forthcoming changes to Housing Benefit. This is of serious concern not only to housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s but also to private lenders.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stable revenue streams are critical to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> housing associations’ ability to maintain existing stock and to repay loans for new supply and improvements to existing stock. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The SFHA views </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occupation restrictions as unfair and incompetent, not least due to the structural mismatch between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e profile of stock and households. Put simply, there are not enough smaller homes. There are also homes where there has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been good reason to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occupation, as in the case of high rise flats and in rural communities where smaller homes simply do not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exist. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The provision of additional funding for DHPs, whilst welcome, is insufficient to mitigate the impact of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. DHPs are intended to provide emergency temporary support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for those facing rent payment difficulties. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotland’s housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">associations are ‘community anchors’. They are often the main agency connecting people with social and welfare services, giving them a significant role in the effective delivery of these services. Many of the mechanisms of welfare reform, including ‘direct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> payment’, have to be realised through the actions of social landlords.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Yet the proposed Local Support Services Framework has yet to recognise this. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The social role of housing associations is fundamental to their activity.  However, this role is not recog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nised sufficiently in the allocation of resources targeted at awareness raising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and support for tenants as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welfare reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is rolled out. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The scale of the wider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welfare </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reforms indicates significant direct financial risks for landlords. The estimated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reductions in tenants’ benefit income </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is critically important to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landlords because a tenant’s propensity to pay rent on time is sensitive to overall levels of household income, not just Housing Benefit. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The transition to direct payments for those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o have limited experience of budgeting may lead to their spending rent money on other perceived priorities.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Leaving aside all of the other welfare refo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rms, Scotland’s housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> face the prospect of havin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g to collect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an additional £21m </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from tena</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts as a result of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">first year of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> restrictions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was previously covered by Housing Benefit. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Changes in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t system consequently have serious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> implications for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> devolved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wider social policies.</span></h2><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Context</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The nee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to get welfare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> right</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The SFHA agrees in principle that the welfare system requires reform; indeed, we are co-signatories to the Scottish Campaign on Welfare Reform.  However, we are greatly concerned by both the nature of the reforms being introdu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ced under the Welfare Reform Act 2012, and the speed with which they are being introduced. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">As the call for evidence stated, a number of welfare reforms will become part of Universal Credit, but there are others which are already being implemented. These i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nclude changes to Housing Benefit and other support provided for housing costs. </span></h3><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Scottish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Housing Associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Support for Housing Costs</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The UK Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">revenue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">subsidy to social housing tenants is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">currently a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">critical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">part of Scotland’s devolved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> housing system.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">recent SFHA survey highlighted the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Housing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for both housing associations and their tenants:</span></h3><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">58% of all HA tenants claim </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, full or partial;</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or most HAs (82%), at least half of their tenants rely on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ousing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to pay rent;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">93% of HAs projected rent arrears to increase in 2013/14, despite just 30% reporting rent arrears increasing over the previous financial year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">80% of housing associations in Scotland are now offering welfare advice; 73% are off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ering debt counselling or money advice. Both figures have increased markedly in the last year because of the programme of welfare reform. </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ul><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Whilst the responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">support for housing costs is reserved to Westminster, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">any reform needs to recognise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e significant differences between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing markets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and policy frameworks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of England and Scotland.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> ‘one size fits all’ approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is creating a range of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> particular challenges for Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, such as: </span></h3><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the greater significance of rural populations in Scotland, coupled with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">concentrations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of deprivation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in urb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant numbers of homes in isolated, excluded locations, which require high levels of maintenance and support, often with high fuel c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">osts and limited communications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more remote areas of Scotland generally have a higher level of digital exclusion, and fewer social services and employment opportunities; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scotland’s rural housing associations have a much lower proportion of smaller properties to facilitate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">downsizing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Scottish private rented sector is relatively smaller and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rents are relatively lower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> than in England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ul><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">As welfare reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">gresses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> burden of support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> society’s most vulnerable people is increasingly falling to organisations such as housing associations, which are not financed directly to undertake such tasks. Scotland’s housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">now trapped </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">in an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> increasingly untena</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ble situation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> with decreasing rental income with which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> address the increasing demand for and cost of supporting tenants impacted by welfare reform. </span></h3><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of changes to the welfare system</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Restrictions</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">To date, the single </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">biggest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of welfare reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">upon Scot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">tish housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the implementation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">restrictions. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Since April 2013, the Government has reduced the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Housing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> entitlement of households in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> social rented sector which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> they deem to be under-occupying their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The Government claims this will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> ease overcrowding, save the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> public purse £500m,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> make better use of stock, impart fairness and improve work incentives. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the savings made to the benefits bill actually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">defray</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> costs elsewhere, to devolved governments, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, social landlords and the third sector.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a recent report for the Scottish Parliament Welfare Reform Committee estimated that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> when the present welfare ref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">orms come into full e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ffect, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">they will take more than £1.6bn a year out of the Scottish economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> equivalent to around £480 a year for every adult of working age.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:normal; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> are making up the shortfall in rent in two ways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">: via</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> DHPs and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">absorbing the cost of rent arrears. A study by COSLA and the Scottish Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">shows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> have experienced a four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">fold increase in the number of applications for DHPs, while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">three quarters of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> councils report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in rent arrears d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">irectly attributable to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> restrictions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. All but one of Scotland’s local authorities with housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">stock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> seen an increase in rent arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, with arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">up £2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> compared to May 2012.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Scottish Housing Regulator </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">(SHR) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">recently u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ndertaken its own survey of the impacts of welfare reform upon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scottish housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">including the impact of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">restrictions upon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> housing associat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ions’ rent arrears performance. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nfortunately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">this data is not yet available. However, based upon our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">own survey of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, there are clear indications of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">adverse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">impact of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">restrictions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">since April</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> this year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Our survey showed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing associations in Scotland were projecting rent arrears to increase during 2013-14 to around 5-6% of rental income. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">compares to 3-4% in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> 2011-12. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Recently published data from the SHR shows that current tenant arrears in the year to March 2013 inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">reased by 6.4% on the previous year.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">expect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bout the period from April 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to be avai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">lable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">SHR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">next few weeks,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">reflect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">our own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">initial findings. Comparable studies from other part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> have all shown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">risin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">g trend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in rent arrears in the wake of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> restrictions. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e would draw </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">attention to the cost-modelling work done by Northern Ireland Federation of Housing Associations (NIFHA), Chartered Institute of Housing in Northern Ireland and the Housing Rights Service which clearly indicates that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">so-called “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bedroom tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> will cost m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">uch more than it saves.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We acknowledge that the UK Government’s rationale for welfare reform is to reduce the benefits bill during this period of “fiscal consolidation”. However, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> restriction has the potential to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the cost </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Housing Benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to the taxpayer, as social tenants feel compelled to seek smaller properties in the more expensive private rented market, given that there are insufficient smaller p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">roperties in the social sector.</span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The claim that the cost of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Housing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> is out of control is highly debatable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in terms of Scottish experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Our research has found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Housing Benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in England has grown by nearly 101% (£10.5bn to £21.1bn), growth in Scotland has been at a more modest 55% (£1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">12bn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to £1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">73bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">).</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">igures s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> faster rate of increase in England is almost wholly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">attributable to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Local Housing Allowance (LHA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and expensive private rents, which the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bedroom tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> will only intensify if social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">tenants downsize </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the private rented sector.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">There</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> are already early signs that the private sector Housing Benefit bill is likely to increase.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> According to the Government’s own forecasts in the current spending review, a total of £37.7bn (out of £95.7bn) is projected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be spent on private renters from 2011/12 to 2014/15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n average this is £9.43</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> per annum on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">LHA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. This compares with the previous spending review, where a total of £23.6b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (out of £63.3b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">) was spent on private renters from 2008/09 to 2010/11 - £7.88b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> aver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">age</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> per year on LHA. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Looking just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">at average spend per year (because the current spending review period is one year longer than the previous review period), that is an increase of £1.55b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> per year spent on private renters in real terms. </span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Discretionary Hous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ayments</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Government has defended the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupancy restrictions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">by stating that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">adequate provision has already been made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">who are worst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">affected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">via the allocation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DHP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scotland’s total DHP fund is £15.5m. This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">insufficient mitigation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">considering that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">an estimated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> £50m is required simply to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">mitigate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bedroom tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">impacts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> alone</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nd is in any case only of temporary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> transitional assistance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ince the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> implementation of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">restrictions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">on 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> April 2013, more than 38,000 housing association tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">faced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a reduction in support with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">rental costs, putting at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">risk £21m of rental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> income for Scottish housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">’s first year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">alone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">SFHA’s research established that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing associations had </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">experienced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a surge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in demand for em</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ergency assistance from tenants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> just a month into implementation of the “bedroom tax”.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">at mid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">May</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> 2013, all but 14 of the 63 housing associations respo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nding to the survey reported receiving large volumes of requests from tenants for DHPs.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Although relatively early into the process, the large volume of DHP applications being submitted underscores the urgency felt across the sector for tenants to access h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ardship assistance before falling into arrears. </span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Tackling overcrowding and making better use of stock</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">contends </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">restrictions will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> ease overcrowding and ensure better use of stock.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">But it </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> rather </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">blunt instrument to</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> solve overcrowding</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">: </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">here are an estimated 250,000 households living in overcrowded conditions, compared to the 660,000 under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">occupying households.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> 59,000 households are overcrowded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">compared to 82,500 under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">occupying.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">With 30,200 currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> on transfer lists, that means that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> just a third of under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">occupying households request to downsize, the number of applicants on transfer lists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will double</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The policy ignores the structural mismatch between the profile of the housing stock and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">households. The plain fact is that people cannot readily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> downsize because there simply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">isn’t the supply of smaller properties for them to move into. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Recent Scottish Government research has found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of the 82,500 households affected, 60,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">d a one bedroom property</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> only around 20,000 one bedroom properties become available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">letting each year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It also undermines best use of stock, e.g. many social landlords have two and three bedroom homes in high rise blocks and, learning from the mis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">takes of the past, have avoided letting them to families with young children. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">t is evident that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under-occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> restrictions are adversely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">affecting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the lives of tenants and the businesses of social landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n six short months, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> scale of disruption caused across the sector clearly show</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> it is the wrong prescription, based on a faulty diagnosis. Moreover, it is highly questionable whether this reform will achieve its stated policy aims. </span></h3><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Concerns about future arrangements</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Direct P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ayments</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ousing associations are concerned about the threats that ‘direct payments’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under Universal Credit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">pose to rental income stream</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Early </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">indications from the direct payment demonstration projects are that rent arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> increase.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Certainly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">has been the experience of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Dunedin Canmore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Housing Association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (DCHA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the Scottish direct payment demonstration project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, with whom we have been working closely over recent months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DCHA has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> had to commit significant additional resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> rent collection </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the ‘direct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> payments’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">regime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, including establishing a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> dedicated debt team</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> to focus solely on income collection.</span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">At the current time DCHA has 686 tenants remaining in the direct payments demonstration project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, representing just 15% of its overall stock. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Where tenants have switched back to having rent paid direct to their landlord,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">they continue to chase those who have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">no arrangement is in place to repay their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">accrued </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DCHA has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">had to incur the costs of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> employing one Full Time Equivalent additional member of staff, plus budget for an additional £7,500 per annum in additional transa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ction charges, and allow for 80</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> hours of overtime per month</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for the demonstration project alone.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">When direct payments are r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">olled out in full with the implementation of universal Credit, DCHA will have to scale up its resources further to tackle the increased burden. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In the words of one of their housing managers: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">“Many tenants will become poorer as a result of the welfare refo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">rm changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">making the task of collecting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">rent more diffi</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">cult.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> The challenge will be to maximise rent collection to minimise arrears levels but there is no doubt in future we will spend more to collect less.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Increased costs, reduced income and increasin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> support to tenants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">is a worrying pattern for all housing associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scottish housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">are not convinced that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">experiences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">demonstration projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">across the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will necessarily be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">applicable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the diverse circumstances in which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Scottish housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">operate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">SFHA is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">concerned about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the apparent lack of progress that the DWP has made to date in enhancing access </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to bank accounts or other forms of budgeting support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">for Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> claimants. In September 2012, DWP Ministers issued a call for a range of suppliers to explore the feasibility of new fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nancial products to help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">claimants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">budget and manage their money.</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Despite enquiring with DWP officials, we have not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">heard any further updates on this matter.</span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local Support Services Framework (LSSF) </span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The DWP has recently set out the framework through which it proposes to support the most vulnerable claimants to ensure that they receive the help they need to apply for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nd subsequently manage their Universal Credit claim.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Although we have been involved in some discussion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> with DWP, Scottish Government and COSLA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> as well as other partner organisations in the Third Sector, SFHA still has a number of concerns about the Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Services Support Framework (LSSF). </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Firstly, the plans for LSSF are still too vague. The task</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">force charged with overseeing the implementation of LSSF comprises statutory agencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> reasons of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">manageability.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> recognition of their key role as stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the DWP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">established a Housing and Voluntary and Community Sector reference group. </span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Whilst DWP officers have made conciliatory noises about the need for an exchange of information between Jobcentres (JCP) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and landlords, no protocol is yet in place. Indeed, at a recent meeting of the DWP, Highland Council and housing associations to discuss the roll out of UC in Inverness, the DWP officer leading the implementation made it explicit there would be no direct c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ommunication between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DWP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">themselves and landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> data sharing between the local authority and the DWP, as had been agreed, for example in the Delivery Partnership agreement between the DWP and Tameside Council. We are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">therefore currentl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">y very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">concerned that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the LSSF arrangements are destined to fail, unless the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">delivery settlement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">properly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">information exchange with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The concept of support for claimants has yet to be backed up with facilities on the ground.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">any Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing associations have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n excellent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">track record in undertaking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">‘wider role’ activities that could contribute to the LSSF, but the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">would need to be scaled up if they were to be applied to meet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the needs of the communities in which the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">y operate. There is also a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">bigger question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">about whether</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">wider community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">activities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">fall within the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> permitted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> aims of a charitable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">association.</span></h3><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SFHA urges the Work and Pensions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee to recognise the extent of the impact of the UK Government’s welfare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reforms on the lives of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tenants and th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e businesses of housing associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Scotland. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">epeal of the under-occupation restrictions would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">address the problems we have outlined</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DHP allocations, even with a recent increase, are insufficient to close the gap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> creating distress. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the short term, the key areas where change is required are: </span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er exceptions relating to under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occupancy for disabled adults, k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inship carers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">households under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">occupying by only one bedroom;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ase-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific easements” for adults with disabilities or other long term conditions who either cannot share a bedroom or have fluctuating needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> often requiring an additional bedroom for sleepover support, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd for separated parents whose children regularly sleep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over, as well as for relatives who care for children t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o allow parents access to work;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Relaxation or transitional protection for people who want to and cannot move because there is no alternative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accommodation. This would involve applying the “grandfathering” principle (i.e. no retrospective application of the restrictions) with a transition period of say three years, which would lapse if a suita</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ble offer was made and refused;.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recognition that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> restriction should not be greater than the actual rent differential given the overcharge to tenants in Scotland due to the difference between the scale of restrictions and the value of actual differentials. </span></li></ul><h2 style="font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have yet to see our sector’s and our lenders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ concerns about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the impact of the forthcoming Universal C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">redit regime being addressed satisfactorily. The financial stability of Scottish housing associations remains under threat as a consequence. </span></h2><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">27 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span></p><p style="border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">From here on, the term “housing associations” will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> be used as a shorthand term for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> the housing association and housing co-operative sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:5.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">SFHA (February 2013), Preparing for Welfare Reform, p.6. Available at Available at </span><a href="http://www.sfha.co.uk/sfha/welfare-reform/welfare-reform-research-and-publications/menu-id-311.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.sfha.co.uk/sfha/welfare-reform/welfare-reform-res</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">earch-and-publications/menu-id-311.html</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (accessed 18th September 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> SFHA (February 2013), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Preparing for Welfare Reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, p.6. Available at Available at </span><a href="http://www.sfha.co.uk/sfha/welfare-reform/welfare-reform-research-and-publications/menu-id-311.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.sfha.co.uk/sfha/welfare-reform/welfare-reform-research-and-publications/menu-id-311.html</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (accessed 18th September 2013) </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> SFHA (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">February 2013), </span><span style="font-family: